 Kingdom","Forfar, Angusshire, Scotland":"Forfar, Forfarshire, Skotland"},"nl":{"1174–1270":"1174–1270","1170–1214":"1170–1214","1190–1242":"1190–1242","1190–1252":"1190–1252","1192–1290":"1192–1290","1193–Male":"1193–Overleden","1197–Male":"1197–Overleden","1190":"1190","about 1192":"circa 1192","about 1190":"circa 1190","1242":"1242","1197":"1197","1252":"1252","1174":"1174","1270":"1270","1193":"1193","1192":"1192","1170":"1170","1290":"1290","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1214":"1214","1224":"1224","Abt 1193":"circa 1193","Douglas and Angus, Angus, Scotland":"Douglas and Angus, Angus, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Forfar, Angus, Scotland":"Forfar, Angus, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","of, Forfar, Angusshre, Scotland":"Forfar, Angus, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Forfar, Angusshire, Scotland":"Forfar, Forfarshire, Schotland"},"en":{"1174–1270":"1174–1270","1170–1214":"1170–1214","1190–1242":"1190–1242","1190–1252":"1190–1252","1192–1290":"1192–1290","1193–Male":"1193–Deceased","1197–Male":"1197–Deceased","1190":"1190","about 1192":"about 1192","about 1190":"about 1190","1242":"1242","1197":"1197","1252":"1252","1174":"1174","1270":"1270","1193":"1193","1192":"1192","1170":"1170","1290":"1290","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1214":"1214","1224":"1224","Abt 1193":"about 1193","Douglas and Angus, Angus, Scotland":"Douglas and Angus, Angus, Scotland, United Kingdom","England":"England","Forfar, Angus, Scotland":"Forfar, Angus, Scotland, United Kingdom","of, Forfar, Angusshre, Scotland":"Forfar, Angus, Scotland, United Kingdom","Forfar, Angusshire, Scotland":"Forfar, Forfarshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Douglas","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from any of various places called from their situation on a river named with Gaelic <i>dubh</i> ‘dark, black’ + <i>glas</i> ‘stream’ (a derivative of <i>glas</i> ‘blue’). There are several localities in Scotland and Ireland so named, but the one from which the surname is derived in most if not all cases is Douglas in Lanarkshire 20 miles south of Glasgow, the original stronghold of the influential Douglas family and their retainers.","History: The family taking their name from Douglas in Lanarkshire were of Flemish origin. They rose to great prominence in the 14th and 15th centuries, controlling the earldoms of Douglas, Morton, and Angus, and later, Queensberry."],"variants":[{"name":"Douglass","meanings":["Scottish and English (Durham and Northumbria): variant of   Douglas  .","History: William Douglass, a physician recognized for his identification and description of an epidemic of scarlet fever, was born <i>c.</i> 1691 in Gifford, Haddington County, Scotland, and settled in Boston in 1718. The abolitionist, orator, and journalist Frederick Douglass assumed the name after escaping from slavery in 1838 and traveling to Massachusetts. Son of a white father and a slave with some Indian blood, he was born Frederick Augustus Washington Bailey <i>c.</i> 1817 in Tuckahoe, MD."]}]},{"name":"Beatrix","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Late Latin personal name, which was borne by a saint martyred in Rome, together with Saints Faustinus and Simplicius, in the early 4th century. The original form of the name was probably <i>Viatrix</i>, a feminine version of <i>Viator</i> ‘voyager (through life)’, which was a favourite name among early Christians. This was then altered by association with Latin <i>Beatus</i> ‘blessed’ (<i>Via-</i> and <i>Bea-</i> sometimes being pronounced the same in Late Latin).  See also  Beatrice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":41,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705188,"age":50,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705189,"age":85,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Beatrix de Douglas was born in 1174, in England. She had at least 3 sons and 2 daughters with Donnchad MacGille Críst - Fifth Earl of Angus. She died in 1270, in her hometown, at the age of 96."},"et":{"1174–1270":"1174–1270","1170–1214":"1170–1214","1190–1242":"1190–1242","1190–1252":"1190–1252","1192–1290":"1192–1290","1193–Male":